com.itko.lisa.test

Class TestExec

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.itko.lisa.test.TestExec
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.itko.lisa.test.ITestExec

    public class TestExec
extends java.lang.Object
implements com.itko.lisa.test.ITestExec
    This is the heart of test execution. The TestCase objects contain the data and behavior regarding how to execute the transactions against the system under test. The TestExec is the state and supporting behaviors for running the test.

    Every time to run a test, you create a TestCase, then create a TestExec for it, then call TestCase.startTest(). Note that this class isn't Serialized, it's created and kept local to the simulator that is running it.

    TestNode subclass developers will spend a lot of time here, so read carefully :)

    See Also:
    TestCase

      • getSysProps

        public static java.util.Properties getSysProps()
        Deprecated. You can use Environment.lisaProps instead
        This method will return the System.getProperties() Properties object. Why we need this is so that we can be sure that the lisa.properties have been added to the System by the time they are returned from this method.

        Therefore, DON'T just use System.getProperties() if you want the lisa.properties to be part of the System Properties. Use this method instead.

        Returns:
        Properties that is all the System properties and everything in the lisa.properties file

      • lookupLisaPropsValue

        public static java.lang.String lookupLisaPropsValue(java.lang.String value)
        There are many places where we want the user to be able to provide a Lisa-looking {{key}} notation for an input, for example, certain places in the run document.

        This class method will take the given value, and if it is in the form {{key}} it will return it's value from the lisa.properties file. Note that it's a class method, and as such, does not have a TestExec context, so you can't set a TestCase- level key/value and hope this method will pick that up. Only in the lisa.properties or any System properties will be seen.

        It'll support all the cool stuff you'd want, like nested properties and the like.

        Parameters:
        value - the String that we think might have a property declaration in it
        Returns:
        the real value, either the same as the value parameter, or the value side of the key that the value parameter was

      • isShootBlanks

        public boolean isShootBlanks()
        LISA can perform property parsing work in 2 modes. One mode, the default, will keep a token in tact if the key w/i it is not found; the other will replace the token with an empty string.
